He saw the disappointment on my face, thought for a moment, and patted the young man’s knee. “As the president of the Clan Association, I can’t really tell you what to do, but on such an important occasion, I suggest you think it over carefully. Besides, who do you want to officiate the funeral? Reverend Ho is very good.”

Reverend Ho? He held services at the church in Chinatown on weekends, but I didn’t know him at all, and neither did my father.
“He’s a complete stranger to my father.”
Mr. Chung shrugged. “You need to have a pastor at the funeral.”
“A friend of mine’s father is a retired pastor,” I said. “He used to frequent my father’s tailor shop.”

Mr. Chung closed his eyes and leaned back in his creaking chair.

