:: Escape {"position":"2350,1725","size":"100,100"}
The pastor ended his speech by scattering a handful of soil onto the coffin. Mourners walked past one by one, each taking turns to say a few words to me. The funeral was over.

After the crowd dispersed, I ran back to the cemetery. In the distance, Mr. Chung’s car was puffing out smoke rings, just like it always did after mediating a “family dispute.”

“You held the funeral you wanted,” I said inwardly to Mr. Chung. Now let me, my father’s flesh and blood, say my last words to him. I turned my gaze to the coffin.

The poem line broke free from its restraints: “And Death Shall Have No Dominion.” Wild grass seeds mixed with dust brushed against my face. In a daze, it felt like a calloused hand was stroking my brow.

