:: Left {"position":"2375,1175","size":"100,100"}
I sighed and left the funeral home. A few blocks away stood a dilapidated building – the Clan Association in Chinatown. I walked up the worn wooden steps, following the scent of cigar smoke towards Wah Chung’s office, the president of the Clan Association. “Come in, young Chen,” a burly figure in a swivel chair by the desk said. “Sit down.” He gestured to a chair with a fat cigar.
“You went to the funeral home?”
“Yes,” I said. “I spoke with the people at Woodside Funeral Home. I believe a graveside ceremony will suffice.”

Mr. Chung nodded without a word. He was a balding man in his fifties, making a career out of local politics. His job involved not only actively participating in community affairs but also resolving family disputes, welcoming clansmen from Hong Kong, and upholding Chinese traditions. His presence was akin to a chieftain, meddling in everything big and small, which annoyed me greatly.

Wah Chung quietly chewed on his cigar before finally saying, “That’s simply impractical. First of all, all Chinese funerals are held in the funeral home’s chapel. That’s where all the friends and pastors can pay their last respects. Secondly, it’s unfair to your father’s friends. You know Woodside is close to Chinatown, and most Chinese funerals are held there. It’s easier for most Chinese people to get there.”

