“Of course,” the salesman said. He seemed sympathetic and friendly, but with a condescending air. I recalled the funerals of classmates’ family members I had attended before, standard Christian ceremonies full of grand displays and formalities. Two Chinese idioms that the elders of the Clan Association often quoted were "入乡随俗" (rù xiāng suí sú) and "随遇而安" (suí yù ér ān), meaning "When in Rome, do as the Romans do" and "Content with one's situation." But I also felt that my father would have stubbornly insisted on the principles he believed in, and there was no reason for me not to do the same.

I heard the roar of jet engines in the distant sky, wondering if there really was a heaven. A sob welled up in my chest, but my face remained blank.

“Your requests will be fulfilled to the best of our ability,” the salesman said, “but I must ask you to consider the process. Our embalmers are highly skilled craftsmen…”
“No, don’t touch him.”

