:: The funeral began {"position":"2350,1600","size":"100,100"}
The funeral began.

Woodside’s chapel was packed with relatives and friends. Looking at this group of relatives I hadn’t seen in years, my heart was filled with mixed emotions.

A funeral home staff member approached, “If you’d like, we can open the casket.”

They had embalmed my father!

My heart suddenly tore open. I smelled the scent of camphor mixed with formaldehyde seeping out from the coffin. The wooden coffin reflected a cold luster under the chandeliers. The staff member’s white-gloved fingertips rested on the coffin lid, like a museum curator preparing to unveil an antique.

“According to the agreement…” I managed to choke out, as if pleading for help. In the distance, Reverend Zhao’s eulogy drifted over like muffled sounds through frosted glass: “…the gift of life must eventually be returned. Mr. Chen, in his life…” I suddenly realized that all the guests were watching me, this “filial son.” I turned my head and saw Jennie sitting beside Joseph. Her eyes met mine, as if noticing that something was wrong with me. I could only force down the boiling anger in my chest.

Recorded hymns played from hidden speakers. Mourners lined up to walk past the closed coffin. As the pallbearers began to move the casket, the funeral director, impeccably dressed in a suit, ghosted to my side. “Excuse me,” he whispered, “Could you please settle the remaining balance as soon as possible? Your Clan Association has already paid their share.” I felt a slight recoil, only muttering a cold “Yes” and quickly escaping.

